        <span id="ChapterQuoteAudio">
        “To meet someone and give your life to them takes a lot of courage!” 
        </span>
        <div id="ChapterText" class="clearfix">
            <!--span id="ChapterByline">
            <span id="textspanlichapter22">ELLIS LI</span><br /><span id="textspanlichapter24">DAUGHTER</span>
            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>I've been asked to share some of the most courageous things that I have done that have made changes in my life. I would have to say that getting married is just about the most courageous thing any one person can do. To meet someone and give your life to them takes a lot of courage! My marrying Kenneth and moving to a farm took a lot of courage. We had a wonderful marriage and a lot of blessings while we lived on that farm, but it was courageous because I never really wanted to live on a farm. But you find someone, you love them, and you're willing to change your past and go on into a whole new way of life. <br />
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                    
                    
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                Another time that took a lot of courage was to accept the mission call to go to Guatemala. It was a total surprise to us when we were called, and it took courage to make preparations and go to a country where we had to learn another language and participate in activities that were totally new to us.<br /><br />

                Later I accepted the call to go to the Mexico City Mission after Kenneth had passed away. That took a lot of courage, too. But when you have the Lord's help, when He asks you and calls you, you just go do it. You just do what He asks you to do, and the blessings come.
            </span>
            <!--span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Living in Rigby has a few advantages that those who live in the “big cities” don't have. The post office folks knew that I was waiting for a call so on the day it was to arrive, and it didn't appear in my mail box, the dreaded wait was extended for a few more hours, the mission papers came in later in the day at the post office so when they arrived the post office folks called my home and Shawn went over to pick them up, called Marlon. Marian. And Taylor then presented the letters to me. And there it was, the temple in Mexico City. My very first thought when I saw the words was, “The temple, thank goodness it is for the temple.” <br /><br />

                    l have to admit that was some disappointment there, and there for some time. Why was the Lord sending me to the very place I had set my heart on that l did not want to go? Had I been counseling the Lord all that time when I knew that I shouldn’t be? Some of my most favorite scriptures are in the book of Jacob in the Book of Mormon, especially this verse: “Seek not to counsel the Lord, but to take counsel from his hand” (Jacob 4:10). This scripture took on a whole new meaning for me. I was troubled for quite some time about the call. I knew I would accept the call but my heart was not not involved, until one morning while reading the Book of Mormon in Spanish. I came upon another scripture that is a favorite, but I didn’t recognize it for a few moments because I was reading it in Spanish. This scripture confirmed to me that Mexico City Temple is exactly where the Lord wanted me. It was Jacob 1:17: “Wherefore, I, Jacob, gave unto them these words as I taught them in the temple, having first obtained mine errand from the Lord.” The impact at this time of a scripture that was very familiar to me in English but not recognized immediately in Spanish was pretty strong and it humbled me considerably and brought a flow of tears and a feeling in my heart that this was indeed right. So, here I go.
 
