        </span>
        <div id="ChapterText" class="clearfix">
            <!--span id="ChapterByline">
            <span id="textspanlichapter22">ALICE CHAU</span><br /><span id="textspanlichapter24">SISTER</span>
            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
                I've been asked if I can remember special times in my life when I have needed to ask forgiveness for a transgression or an unkindness that I did. There are a couple of them that I remember vividly.
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                    
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                One of them was early in our marriage, and we had a particular neighbor who was difficult for us to get along with. We had some difficult times working together—not socially, but mostly in the work element. I said some very, very unkind things to him. Within a couple of hours I knew that I had to go and knock on that door and ask for forgiveness. I was able to do that. The Lord helped me to do it. It was very, very difficult for me to do, but I was ashamed of what I had said. It didn't need to be said, it was my own opinion, and it was very unkind. I was ashamed of how I had behaved. So I went up and knocked on the door and asked them to forgive me. Everything was okay after that.
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory3-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory3');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory3" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    I had one other experience just this last year. We had a difficulty with a dishwasher that wasn't functioning properly. It wasn't cleaning the dishes. Time after time I got so upset because I had to wash the dishes after I took them out of the dishwasher. I called the supplier and found out that I was about three months past the warranty. Of course they would not do anything to help me with that dishwasher. I hadn't had it that long, either, but the warranty was gone. <br /><br />

                    One morning when I was in a vicious mood, I picked up the phone and called the dealer for Whirlpool in Idaho Falls. I told him how I felt, and I let him have it. I said, “I feel that I have not had a good experience with the appliance. I think that you should have at least helped me find out what the problem was.” I really let him have it over the telephone, and then I just hung up. The poor man! He just listened. It was not his fault, and it had nothing to do with him; he was just in the store. It took me about an hour and then I went back, picked up the phone, called the store again, and said, “I don't know who I spoke to about an hour ago, but I was very unkind, and I need to apologize. I'm sorry for what I said, and could you please tell the young man that I called back to apologize.” It was difficult for me to do.<br /><br />

                    I'm sure there are other instances in my life when I've had to ask for forgiveness for my actions and my words, but these two stand out. 
                </span>

